		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">RetroKevin wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Over the last few months I've been slowly going down the rabbit hole that is NES game development. Resources were few and far between</div><br /><br />Maybe it's not fair to only look at this relatively to other systems, but the NES is amazingly well documented in this day and age, and I can't think of any other &quot;retro&quot; videogame platform that is even close to being as as thoroughly defined as the NES, when looking through online resources. The C64 and Amiga might, but I think that's as far as you can go.<br /><br />I worked on reverse engineering a PCE game the other day, and holy crap - just figuring out how the games communiate with the graphics chip was a wild goose chase between five different websites, each with fractured pieces of information that would occasionally contradict eachother. And that's actually one of the platforms that should be relatively well known.

		

